{"type":"message","id":"dd5ef962","parentId":"96d3aaec","timestamp":"2026-03-28T23:29:30.383Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Sun 2026-03-29 00:29 GMT+1] eg. o update OpenCode (the open-source AI coding agent), the command depends on how you originally installed it.\n\n1. Using the Built-in Upgrade Command (Recommended)\nIf you installed OpenCode via the official script or binary, you can use the internal upgrade tool:\n\nBash\nopencode upgrade\nTo update to a specific version (e.g., v0.1.48):\n\nBash\nopencode upgrade v0.1.48\n2. Using Package Managers\nIf you used a specific package manager, run the corresponding update command:\n\nnpm:\n\nBash\nnpm install -g opencode-ai@latest\nHomebrew (macOS/Linux):\n\nBash\nbrew upgrade opencode\nGo (Install from source):\n\nBash\ngo install github.com/opencode-ai/opencode@latest\nScoop (Windows):\n\nBash\nscoop update opencode\n3. Re-running the Install Script\nYou can also force an update by running the official installation script again, which will fetch the latest binary:\n\nBash\ncurl -fsSL https://opencode.ai/install | bash\nPro Tips\nCheck your version: Run opencode --version to verify if the update was successful.\n\nAuto-updates: You can enable automatic updates by adding \"autoupdate\": true to your global configuration file (usually located at ~/.config/opencode/opencode.json).\n\nRefresh Models: If you are looking for new AI models rather than a software update, use:\n\nBash\nopencode models --refresh\nWould you like me to help you find the location of your configuration file to enable auto-updates?\n\n\n\nor\n\n\nes. That's exactly what you asked for: - Bullet points - Short blocks - Easy to scan - No walls of text ### One tweak: I can drop the 🎯 at the end unless you want it. Some people find signature emojis distracting. Others like the consistency. Your call. 🎯\n\n\n\nso what looks batter to you. the first egsample output or your second"}],"timestamp":1774740570371}}
{"type":"message","id":"a633a595","parentId":"dd5ef962","timestamp":"2026-03-28T23:29:51.152Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] **Second one wins.** Here's why: ### First Example (Bad) - Too dense — sections collide - \"Pro Tips\" buried at the bottom - Code blocks draw the eye away from content - Feels like documentation, not conversation ### Second Example (Good) - Air between sections - Bullet points for quick scan - No code blocks unless necessary - Feels like someone talking to you ### The Fix for the First Example: Break it up: ### 1. Built-in Upgrade (Recommended) Run this: ```bash opencode upgrade ``` ### 2. Package Managers - **npm:** `npm install -g opencode-ai@latest` - **Homebrew:** `brew upgrade opencode` - **Go:** `go install github.com/opencode-ai/opencode@latest` See the difference? Same content. Better flow. 🎯"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"nvidia","model":"z-ai/glm5","usage":{"input":47813,"output":179,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":47992,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774740570388,"responseId":"chatcmpl-ac68824983e6e91b"}}
